{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UAd4MA1zN5r6ATZojcUoSw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"RabbitMQ doesn't expose `rabbitmq_up` natively - that's typically a metric added by the Prometheus RabbitMQ exporter (the separate prometheus-exporter for RabbitMQ). The native RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin exposes metrics like `rabbitmq_alarms_*`, etc.\n\nThe `rabbitmq_up` metric is a synthetic metric usually generated by exporters like the `rabbitmq_exporter`. \n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements: \"Prometheus shows 3 RabbitMQ targets UP and query rabbitmq_up returns 3 samples.\"\nSo they're saying the 3 targets show as up in the Prometheus targets page, and when querying `rabbitmq_up`, it returns 3 samples - which would only happen if that metric is actually being exported. The native RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't generate `rabbitmq_up`, so this must be coming from the `rabbitmq_exporter` tool or Prometheus is generating the `up` metric for each target.\n\nWait, I'm realizing Prometheus automatically creates an `up` metric for every scrape target, so `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` would give 3 samples when all targets are healthy. But the query specifically asks for `rabbitmq_up`, not just `up`. Maybe this is a custom metric added through a recording rule or relabeling, or perhaps the RabbitMQ exporter itself exposes it. Let me look more carefully at what metrics are available from the RabbitMQ endpoints - there might be an identity or status metric I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":645,"cache_read_input_tokens":37444,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":645},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8703155a-1cea-4b1b-b988-4